data.jamchart_notes: At the time of its debut, nobody had heard "Hungersite" before and it immediately establishes itself as a jam vehicle. Great rocking motif before the segue into the live debut of "Dripfield".

data.jamchart_notes: Ultra-funky molasses jamming. Trevor puts on a clinic concocting murderous bass lines while Rick lets his inner SRV come out to play, absolutely scorching blues soloing.
Builds up an impressive head of steam with aggressive Nord work from Peter before cooling and smoothly transitioning -> to "Into the Myst."

data.jamchart_notes: Peter leads the way into a blissy progression in a heated initial jam section. Breaks into dark, sparse funk with nasty, nasty clav and then an ascending and powerful riff. Serious growl and mojo to this ending with Trevor going absolutely wild.

data.jamchart_notes: Absolute ripper until 18 minutes in when band settles into funky, synthy slow jam followed by a gorgeous blissy cooldown, and finally ending majestically and triumphantly by building back into a soaring melodic peak. Brilliant improv journey.

data.jamchart_notes: Foregoing the initial rocking section and peak we’ve seen in many 2023 versions, the band immediately settles for a quieter, gentler jam. Results in Rick finding a pretty riff with around 5 mins to go that everyone hooks onto and builds into a really pretty glory peak.

data.jamchart_notes: Eschews the usual blistering and fast-paced jam in favour of a laid-back and major-key space. Shorter version that will draw you in for repeated listens.

data.jamchart_notes: Builds momentum like many '23 versions but begins to stray from normal when Peter hits the clav with some subtle delay. Spuds is an absolute WORKHORSE as he keeps the propulsive tempo up. Rick finds a melody that he likes and Goose shreds to a peak of epic proportions. Final night of tour throw-down.

data.jamchart_notes: Goes absolutely balls-to-the-walls for the first jam, getting to high speeds and intensity while Rick absolutely unleashes on the eager crowd. Back half is a nice and patient dual-guitar space that segues nicely into "Dripfield" to complete the Driptych.

data.jamchart_notes: The band sits in Type I "Hungersite" territory for most of the jam, giving the impression of a conscious effort to resist full peak mode for as long as possible. By the time they get there, there's some undertones of heavy rock and Cotter leads into a half-time shred mode for the final minute that's absolutely amazing.

data.footnote: With Mad World teases from Rick and Cantaloupe Island teases from Peter.
data.jamchart_notes: Peter keeps the familiar "Hungersite" peak fresh with a repeated descending lick, beefing up his usual comping behind Rick's solo. Barely slows down at all before the disco-delay clav comes in like this version's counterparts from 11/20/23 and Chateau Sessions. Rick throws in some digital sauce as the disco gets more vicious and hits a final peak.

This first jam is the Cotter show. The man is on FIRE through the usual peak and then goes hand-in-hand with Rick into an angular, dark zone for the final few minutes. A motif that is begging to be explored more by Goose.

data.jamchart_notes: Eschews the typical Type I "Hungersite" peak and shifts immediately into gorgeous bliss. Rick weaves some incredible earworm melodies to a peak before the band quiets, beginning a LONG and patient build to a final explosion. Excellent use of phaser piano from Peter.
data.shownotes: Atlas Dogs was played in its Indie-Groove arrangement for the first time since October 11, 2022 (130 shows). Bloodbuzz Ohio was played for the first time since September 28, 2023 (56 shows). Sinnerman was played for the first time since May 2, 2023 (87 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: Ecstasy. Infectious optimism. Pure Joy. Rick finds a repeating hook at 7:45 that he builds around before an explosion of guitar Rock Goddery. Every time you think he's found the apex of energy within the peak, he unlocks a new level of earworm shredding. He then slows down, brilliantly going back into the earlier riff before deciding to hose down the crowd one last time. This song DELIVERS as a set closer.

data.jamchart_notes: All the 2024 "Hungersite" jams were leading to this moment. Absolute masterclass in restraint and gradual ramp-up from Cotter as Peter finds a simple phrase on the clav to repeat dreamily for several minutes. When the peak comes, it barely seems like the energy needs to ramp up, but it's just the cathartic conclusion needed. Unfortunate bingo ball pull for "Flodown" can't even dampen the ending.

data.jamchart_notes: Gets minor, dark, and Westville "Rockdale"-y with all the best notes. Frenetic and uneasy piano gets cloudy among busy work from Rick as Cotter propels the whole thing. Quiets after a spell and seems to be building to a huge major-key explosive finish, but the band stays minor and Peter pours on some distorted clav as they crash through a final peak and fade > to "Dripfield" before you have time to collect your thoughts.

data.jamchart_notes: Less high-octane and more of a grounded rock jam dominates the first 18 minutes or so, then the band opts for the second huge post-peak "Hungersite" jam of the summer. It's pure Ted Tapes energy, coming close to "Dragonfly" or "Bob Don" with its patient and dreamy vibe - one of the coolest segments of the tour. BEAUTIFUL Trevor.

data.jamchart_notes: An unusually soft and contemplative approach to the jam at first. Trevor is the lead instrument here, laying down gorgeous melodies. When Rick asserts himself, Trevor is right there matching and augmenting the musical ideas. The familiar slow build picks up more and more steam as Cotter gradually increases the intensity until we find ourselves in a typically fiery Hungersite jam that takes a shocking turn into Make The Move.
